\begin_layout Section
Mathematical Foundations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The standard Bayesian approach / Single person inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model a single measurement 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in Z=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 based on the underlying and a priori unknown parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X=\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

 via the deterministic forward map 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi:X\rightarrow Z$
\end_inset

, perturbed by an measurement error 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 which is normally distributied with a known or estimated covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $e\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,\Sigma\right)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z=\Phi\left(x\right)+e
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given this description it is straightforward to simulate measurements for
 given parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the so called forward problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following we will be interested in solving the inverse-problem in
 a stochastic setting, that is given some probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{Z}\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 on the measurements, what can we say about the distribution of the unknown
 parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main tool in this proceeding will be Bayes' Theorem, which is easily
 derived in its distributional form from the definition of the conditional
 probability distribution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The conditional probability density of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 given the occurence of the value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left(y|X=x\right):=\frac{\rho\left(x,y\right)}{\rho\left(x\right)},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 is the joint density of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the marginal density of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the density of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 marginalized over all possible 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left(x\right):=\int_{y}\rho\left(x,y\right)\mathrm{d}y.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Succesive insertion of these identities leads to the continious / density
 form of Bayes' Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left(x|Y=y\right):=\frac{\rho\left(x,y\right)}{\rho\left(y\right)}=\frac{\rho\left(y|x\right)\rho\left(x\right)}{\rho\left(y\right)}=\frac{\rho\left(y|x\right)\rho\left(x\right)}{\int_{x}\rho\left(y|x\right)\rho\left(x\right)\mathrm{d}x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
This formula, constituting the heart of Bayesian statistics, tells us how
 to reconstruct the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

posterior distribution
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(x|y\right)$
\end_inset

 of the unknown parameter x given data y, using the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

likelihood
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(y|x\right)$
\end_inset

 of y given x as well as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prior
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 denoting our prior assumptions of the density of x.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Note that for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 the prior and posterior both are probability distributions in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, whilst the likelihood would be in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 but is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Likelihood function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Note that the denominator, also called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

evidence
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and thus is merely a scaling constant, preserving the probability density
 property of having total measure one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Whilst the model for our measurements directly tells us the likelihood 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left(y|x\right)\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\Phi\left(x\right),\Sigma\right),
\]

\end_inset

the choice of the prior still remains an open question.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Prior estimation based on cohort data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume we have given not just one measurement, but a density of measurements
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{z}$
\end_inset

, e.g.
 the sampling distribution of finitely many measurements 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=\left(z_{1},\,z_{2},\,z_{3},\,...,\,z_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the prior itself as random variable we can now formulate the
 likelihood function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L\left(\pi|\rho_{z}\right)=\int_{z}\rho\left(z|\pi\right)\rho_{z}\left(z\right)\mathrm{dz}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left(z|\pi\right)=\int\rho\left(z|x\right)\pi\left(x\right)\mathrm{d}x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

