\begin_layout Section
Prior estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we know how to handle a single measurement let us raise the question
 of how to handle multiple measurements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A naive approach would adapt the likelihood to represent the joint probability
 of the measurements:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(x)=\Pi L(x_{i})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While this indeed is correct assuming i.i.d.
 measurements, a simple example shows the failure for non identically distribute
d random variables:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Bob Alice product 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming non i.i.d.
 measurements 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 we can model this epistemic uncertainty through a categorical distribution
\end_layout

